          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that took courage to lay out so honestly — and what you're describing matters. Heavy legs, disrupted sleep, lost appetite, dreading runs, elevated resting HR. You're not just having a rough week. These are your body's signals stacking up, and they deserve to be taken seriously.\n\nHere's the thing about your timeline: **10 weeks is actually enough runway — but only if you're able to absorb training.** Right now, your body is telling you it can't. Pushing harder into that state doesn't build fitness; it erodes it. The risk isn't taking easy days. The risk is grinding through the next two weeks and arriving at the start line already depleted.\n\nBefore I say more — **what's your read on what's been driving the poor sleep?** Is this life stress bleeding in, or does it feel more like your body just won't switch off after runs?\n\n---\n\nThat said, I want to share what I'm seeing from a training standpoint, if you're open to it.\n\nYour resting HR being up 8 bpm for a sustained week is one of the clearest objective signs that your system is under-recovered. Combined with the appetite and motivation changes, this pattern is consistent with what sports scientists call *functional overreaching* — a state where the training load has outpaced your recovery. The good news: it's reversible, and relatively quickly, with the right response.\n\nWhat I'd suggest considering is a **modified recovery week** — not stopping, but shifting the next 5–7 days to easy-only running at the lower end of your easy pace (around 5:50–6:27/km), shorter durations, zero intensity work. Think of it as a reset that *protects* your peak weeks, not a detour from them.\n\n**10 weeks to a 1:45 half marathon is workable from your current fitness base.** But week 1 of those 10 needs to be a recovery week, not a build week. You'd still have 8–9 weeks of quality preparation ahead — which is genuinely enough.\n\nOne thing I want to name: if the sleep disruption, appetite loss, and dread persist even after easing the training load, it's worth a conversation with your doctor. Sometimes what looks like overtraining has other contributors, and that's outside what I can assess as your coach.\n\nWhat feels possible to you this week — what would a lighter training week actually look like in your life?"
        }
      ],
